<Layout title="BenVG | About">
  <article class="about-container">
    <h1 class="about-title">Hi, I'm Ben van Glabbeek</h1>

    <img
      src="/images/ben-portrait.jpg"
      alt="Ben van Glabbeek"
      class="about-portrait"
    />

    <div class="about-section">
      <p>
        My path has been shaped by two seemingly different worlds that share profound connections: technology transformation and leadership development. Through both, I've discovered the importance of adaptability, continuous learning, and finding joy in the quest of creating value.
      </p>

      <p>
        After navigating the technology landscape from startups to Fortune 500 companies, I see transformation not just as a business strategy but as a philosophy. I've led teams in reimagining what's possible when technology and human ingenuity converge. Whether designing cloud solutions, modernizing legacy systems, or exploring the frontiers of AI, I've found that the most meaningful work happens at the intersection of technical excellence and human-centered design.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="about-section">
      <h2>The Four Principles</h2>
      <p>
       Throughout my journey, I've developed a framework of four interconnected principles that guide my approach to both technology and leadership:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Flow:</strong> Thinking end-to-end, from concept to customer, is essential. Removing barriers between teams and eliminating wait times creates an environment where ideas can flow smoothly into impactful outcomes.</li>
        <li><strong>Quality:</strong> Quality isn't just inspection at the end—it's built into every step. Drawing inspiration from lean, effective systems surface problems immediately and make solving them everyone's responsibility.</li>
        <li><strong>Joy:</strong> Joy transcends momentary happiness. It's what happens when people connect deeply with meaningful work and understand how their contributions matter. Creating joy means helping teams connect with purpose rather than just executing tasks.</li>
        <li><strong>Value:</strong> The most beautiful solutions fail if they don't deliver real value. This emerges at the intersection of technical capabilities and people, ensuring the creation of solutions that truly matter.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="about-section">
      <h2>Where Trails Cross</h2>
      <p>
        This blog represents the confluence of my professional journey and personal passions—a place where different paths intersect and fresh perspectives emerge. Here, I share insights, experiments, and reflections that span the landscapes I traverse:
      </p>
        <ul>
          <li>How emerging AI capabilities and engineering practices are creating new paths forward</li>
          <li>The delicate art of transforming organizations while respecting their unique cultures</li>
          <li>Leadership lessons learned through experimentation and continuous learning</li>
          <li>The search for simplicity and meaning in increasingly complex systems</li>
          <li>My adventures on the trail and what I'm doing next</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="about-section">
      <h2>Outside the Office</h2>
      <p>
        As Scoutmaster of Troop 10, I apply my leadership philosophy in a completely different context. Our troop operates on principles that parallel: Scout-led, learning by doing, valuing community over self, and maintaining a pragmatic focus on progress over perfection. This role has taught me that leadership development is most effective when people face real challenges and when they're given the space to make mistakes and learn.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="about-section">
      <h2>Experimentation and Learning</h2>
        <p>
          Thinking independently and adapting to your environment yields better results than blindly adopting packaged methodologies. Constant experimentation—through small, focused efforts to improve flow, quality, joy, and value—builds knowledge systematically. Some experiments succeed brilliantly; others fail instructively. All provide learning that builds toward better systems and more effective leadership.
        </p>
        <p>
          Sometimes the best insights come when stepping away from familiar environments to gain fresh perspective. Whether in the wilderness, at the keyboard, or at the whiteboard, changing context reveals solutions previously hidden.
        </p>
    </div>

